Basic HTML Infrastructure:
<!DOCTYPE html> /*Tells the browser that we are using HTML5*/
<html>
  <head>
        <title></title>
  </head>
	  <body>
	  </body>
</html>

Main HTML Tags:
	• Paragraph: <p> </p>
	• Bold: <strong> </strong>
	• Italicize: <em> </em>
	• Ordered List: <ol> </ol>
		○ Must include before you list the items
	• Listed Items in the Ordered List: <li> </li> (Uses Numbering)
	• Unlisted Items in the Ordered List: <ul> </ul>(uses dots)
	• Line Break (         ): <br> 
		○ Adds a line of blank space
	• Horizontal Line Break (_________): <hr> 
	• Image Tag: <img src="   "> (This tag is self-closing)
	• Anchor Tag: <a href=" "> </a>
	• Form Tag: <form> form elements </form>
	• Divide Content Tag: <div> form/paragraph/etc </div>
	• Span Tag (Inline Element): <span> </span>
		○ We can add styles to a specific inline tag (One element in a form)

Image Tag Specifications:
	• Tag with source: <img src" " > 
		○ Source is where the image is coming from
	• Adding Width & Size: <img src " " width="x" height="x">
	• Adding a description (alt): <img src="x" alt="description"
		○ Alt is a description of the image
		○ Good practice as it helps anyone with a disability view the website correctly
		
Relative vs Absolute Path:
	• Relative Path: Uses the file protocol, so you can't access it away from computer
		○ Example: file:///C:/Users/krstob/Desktop/HTML%20Files/index.html
	• Absolute Path: Accessing the html file from Http, so everyone can view it across the globe
		○ Example: https://www.sublimetext.com/3

HTML vs HTML5:
	• HTML5 doesn't affect older websites
	• HTML5 adds support on all main browsers
	• HTML5 features mobile browser support
	• HTML5 adds Semantic Elements (descriptors)

Form Tag Specifications:
	• Form Tag: <form> Form Tag Stuff </form>
	• Input Type: <input type = "text">
	• Example: <form> <input type="text"> </form>
	• To Submit a Form: <input type="submit" value="ButtonName(Register)">
	• To reset a form: <input type="reset">
	• To make a field required: <input type="text" required>
	• Password Field: <input type="password" minlength="5">
	• To make sure you input an email: <input type="email">
	• Date Fields (birthdate): <input type="email">
	• Button Input Types (Radio): <input type="radio">
		○ 
		○ The Name variable is so the radio buttons know of each other so the user can only select one button
	• Button Input Checkbox: <input type="checkbox">
		○ 
	• Drop Down Menus: Select One Option
		○ 
	• Drop Down Menu: Select Multiple Options: <select multiple>

